## functions

icc <- function(x, nms, type, ...) {
  
  res <- ICC(x[, ..nms], ...)$results
  res[res$type == type, "ICC"]
}

pull_fixef <- function(x, nms = c("term", "b", "se", "tstat")) {
  
  res <- coef(summary(x))
  res <- cbind(rownames(res), data.table(res))
  names(res) <- nms
  
  res
  
}

pull_trcor <- function(x) attr(VarCorr(x)$subj.1, "correlation")[2, 1]


mean_crosstask_cor <- function(x) {
  
  x <- x[[1]]
  cross_wave <- x[grep("wave1", colnames(x)), grep("wave2", colnames(x))]
  
  tanh(mean(atanh(cross_wave[row(cross_wave) != col(cross_wave)])))
  
}

2 trial-level: LME

Fitted with Gang Chen-style covariance structure. 6 random-effect (co)variance parameters are estimated (in grey):

The first two rows/columns correspond to the â€˜interceptsâ€™, separately in wave 1 (row 1) and wave 2 (row 2). Here, the intercepts are the average of hi and lo trialtypes. The second two rows/columns correspond to the â€˜slopesâ€™ in waves 1 and 2. Here the slope is the difference between hi and lo trialtypes. This model assumes that intercepts and slopes are uncorrelated. What we are interested in is \(r_2\), the cross-wave (testâ€“retest) correlation in the hilo contrast.

## fit models

f_tr <- paste0(
  key_schaefer$parcel, 
  " ~ hilo * wave + (0 + mean_wave1 + mean_wave2 | subj) + (0 + hilo_wave1 + hilo_wave2 | subj)"
  )

m_tr <- mclapply(f_tr, function(x) lmer(as.formula(x), data_hilo), mc.cores = n_core/2)
m_tr_cors <- unlist(lapply(m_tr, pull_trcor))

r_tr_cors <- data.table(value = m_tr_cors, roi = rois)



## plot

r_tr_cors_filter <- r_tr_cors %>% filter(!is.nan(value))

p_tr_lme_dist <- r_tr_cors_filter %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(value)) +
  geom_histogram(fill = "grey40", bins = 20) +
  
  labs(
    x = "test-retest correlation, hilo contrast, Stroop LSall", 
    caption = paste0(nrow(r_tr_cors) - nrow(r_tr_cors_filter), " NaN obs removed")
    )

ggsave(
  here("out", "test_retest", "figs", "hilo-test-retest_lme-gang_dist_lsall-stroop.pdf"), 
  p_tr_lme_dist, 
  dev = "pdf", height = 3, width = 4
  )

3 trial-level: hierarcical bayesian models

Similar structure as LME above. As in Chen et al.Â (2021), assume response is distributed as Studentâ€™s t (providing robustness against outliers). Same priors used here as in Chen et al.Â (2021), which are the default priors in brms for this model structure.

fname_results_hbm <- here("out", "test_retest", "fits_hba_chenstyle_Stroop_lsall.RDS")
should_fit_models <- any(!file.exists(fname_results_hbm))

3.1 fit models

# task_i <- 1
# roi_i <- 1


## prep data

data_hilo_l <- 
  melt(
    data_hilo, 
    id.vars = c(trial_cols, "mean_wave1", "mean_wave2", "hilo_wave1", "hilo_wave2"), 
    variable.name = "roi", value.name = "bold"
  )

model_cols <- c("subj", "task", "wave", "roi", "hilo", "mean_wave1", "mean_wave2", "hilo_wave1", "hilo_wave2", "bold")
data_hilo_l <- data_hilo_l[, ..model_cols]


## model info

f <- formula(
  bold ~ hilo * wave + 
    (0 + mean_wave1 + mean_wave2 | subj) + 
    (0 + hilo_wave1 + hilo_wave2 | subj)
  )


## subset and format

l <- split(data_hilo_l, data_hilo_l$roi)

## fit

start_time <- Sys.time()
plan(multicore, workers = 28)

fits <- brm_multiple(
  formula = f,
  data = l,
  family = student,
  warmup = 1000, iter = 2000, chains = 4,
  control = list(adapt_delta = 0.95),
  combine = FALSE,
  seed = 0
  )

plan(sequential)
run_time <- Sys.time() - start_time

names(fits) <- names(l)

## save

saveRDS(fits, fname_results_hbm)

print(run_time)

3.4 variance ratios

ratios  <- lapply(

    fits,

        function(x) {

        varcor <- VarCorr(x)
        resid_sd <- varcor$residual$sd[1]
        subj_mean_sd <- sqrt(mean(varcor$subj$sd[c("mean_wave1", "mean_wave2"), "Estimate"]^2))
        subj_hilo_sd <- sqrt(mean(varcor$subj$sd[c("hilo_wave1", "hilo_wave2"), "Estimate"]^2))

        ratio_mean <- (resid_sd / subj_mean_sd)^2
        ratio_hilo <- (resid_sd / subj_hilo_sd)^2

        data.table(
          resid_sd = resid_sd, subj_mean_sd = subj_mean_sd, subj_hilo_sd = subj_hilo_sd,
          ratio_mean = ratio_mean,
          ratio_hilo = ratio_hilo
          )

    }
)

ratios <- rbindlist(ratios, idcol = "roi")


p_vardecomp <- ratios %>%
    
  melt(id.vars = "roi") %>%
  filter(variable %in% c("resid_sd", "subj_mean_sd", "subj_hilo_sd")) %>%
  
    ggplot(aes(variable, value)) +
    geom_boxplot(width = 0.2, fill = "grey40") +
  
  coord_flip() +
  labs(x = "parameter", y = "posterior mean", title = "variance decomposition")

p_vardecomp

ggsave(here("out", "test_retest", "figs", "variance_ratio_lsall-stroop.pdf"), p_vardecomp, width = 4, height = 3)
